&lt;h3 id=&#34;what-does-shiro-mean-in-korean-싫어&#34;&gt;What Does Shiro Mean in Korean (싫어)?&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;“Shiro” (written as &lt;strong&gt;싫어&lt;/strong&gt; in Hangul) is used when you really &lt;strong&gt;dislike something&lt;/strong&gt;. It can mean:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I don’t want to&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I hate it&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I dislike that&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It’s a strong emotional refusal—not just a calm “no.”&lt;/p&gt;
